      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Fail-fast startup errors are only observed in a short window, then silently ignored.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/startuporchestrator/startup_orchestrator.go",
          "goseg/startuporchestrator/startup_orchestrator_test.go",
          "goseg/main.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`waitForFailFastErrors` returns nil when its 250ms timeout expires even if fail-fast workers are still running and may fail later.",
          "`Bootstrap` invokes health once (`return o.health(ctx)`), so there is no ongoing reconciliation for delayed fail-fast worker errors during normal runtime.",
          "Tests validate near-immediate fail-fast errors (e.g., 20ms), but do not enforce behavior for failures after the timeout window."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Make fail-fast monitoring persistent: store terminal worker errors in shared state and have `health` report them without a fixed startup-only timeout; alternatively keep a supervisor goroutine that propagates late fail-fast errors to a shared fatal channel consumed by startup/runtime orchestration.",
