      "id": "review::.::holistic::abstraction_fitness::wrapper_chain_without_policy_gain::714ca6df",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "Several runtime wrapper layers are pass-through and increase call depth without new policy.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/broadcast/state_lifecycle.go",
          "goseg/broadcast/loop.go",
          "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_api.go",
          "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_methods.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "Broadcast lifecycle exposes paired wrappers (`LoadStartramRegionsWithRuntime` -> `LoadStartramRegionsWithRuntimeState`, `bootstrapBroadcastState` -> `bootstrapBroadcastStateWithRuntime`) that mainly re-check nil and forward.",
          "Broadcast loop frequently reconstructs default runtime wrappers (`newBroadcastLoopRuntimeWithDefault`) for operations that immediately delegate.",
          "WiFi runtime service repeatedly performs prepare/resolve forwarding before invoking runtime methods, while runtime methods already wrap command-level operations and defaults."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Collapse pass-through wrapper pairs into one canonical entry point per operation, and centralize nil/default resolution once at construction. Keep wrappers only when they enforce distinct policy (auth, retries, timeout semantics); otherwise remove redundant forwarding layers.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
