    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::import_phase_primary_error_shadowed_by_publish_error::59613d99": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::import_phase_primary_error_shadowed_by_publish_error::59613d99",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Importer phase orchestration can hide the primary workflow error behind a secondary publish error",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/importer/importer.go",
          "goseg/importer/importer_test.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "In runImportPhases(), after a non-nil workflowErr and successful cleanup, `if publishErr != nil { return fmt.Errorf(\"import phase transition publish failed ...\") }` executes before `return workflowErr`.",
          "This means when both workflow execution and phase/error publishing fail, callers can receive only the publish failure and lose the main import failure context.",
          "Current tests cover successful status emission but do not assert behavior when workflowErr and publishErr happen together."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Change runImportPhases() to preserve the workflow error as primary context and join publishErr (and cleanupErr when present), e.g. `return fmt.Errorf(\"import failed for %s: %w\", patp, errors.Join(workflowErr, publishErr))`; add a test that forces both failures and asserts the returned error contains both causes.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "auto_resolved",
      "note": "Disappeared from scan \u2014 likely fixed",
      "first_seen": "2026-03-05T17:28:56+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-05T17:28:56+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-03-05T18:32:10+00:00",
